actices draws on a substantial body of new archival material to expose the roadblocks still present in current practices and imagine new alternatives. In this landmark book, Laura Doan clarifies the ethical value and political purpose of identity history—and indeed its very capacity to give rise to innovative practices borne of sustained exchange between queer studies and critical history. Disturbing Practices insists on taking seriously the imperative to step outside the logic of identity to address questions as yet unasked about the modern sexual past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aLesbiansxSexual behavior. 0aQueer theory. 0aWomen and war. 0aWomenxSexual behavior. 70(DE-601)1042707050(DE-588)4018202-2aFrau2gnd 70(DE-601)1043600700(DE-588)4033114-3aKrieg2gnd 70(DE-601)1058063150(DE-588)4116485-4aSexualverhalten2gnd 70(DE-601)5811168520(DE-588)7628620-4aQueer-Theorie2gnd 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  ahuman sexuality, gws, psychology, lesbian studies, lgbtqia, gay, homosexual, homosexuality, womens work experience, friendships, communities, new archival material, multidisciplinary, ethical value, political purpose, identity, critical history, 20th century, intellectual paradigms, queer theory, cultural, social issues, society, sexual behavior, discipline problem, gender.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022600158640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226001753423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226001753/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles